Not really. I personally try to keep tag and attribute names as short as 
possible since they get repeated so much and therefore add to file size 
bloat if they&#39;re to long. So e.g. instead of src-id I might have used 
src. And I might have used the word genome instead of chromosome in this 
case - since the two mean the same thing within the context of NEAT 
AFAIK. These are pretty trivial/petty points though. Most schemas I see 
these days define lower case tag/attribute names (e.g. xhtml / xforms 
tags are all lower case) -  note that XML is case sensitive.

Regarding what sort of data to store, my initial instinct is to save the 
entire current population both at intervals and at the end of a run - 
creating a population.xml file. Within that file we would store a list 
of &lt;chromosome&gt; tags and at the top some additional data about the run, 
in fact I imagine it would look something like...

